metadata.title: Bell OH-58 Kiowa
aws::graph::propositions: Bell OH-58 Kiowa International Transfers and Replacement
Croatia requested 16 OH-58D Kiowa helicopters in 2016.
Tunisia requested 24 OH-58D Kiowa helicopters in 2016.
Croatia and Tunisia were the first nations to request OH-58D Kiowa helicopters.
Croatia received the first batch of 5 OH-58D Kiowa helicopters on 30 June 2016.
The first batch of OH-58D Kiowa helicopters for Croatia was delivered to the Zadar-Zemunik air base.
Greece was granted 70 OH-58D Kiowa helicopters via a Foreign Military Sales arrangement in early 2018.
The OH-58D Kiowa helicopters for Greece were initially stationed at Hellenic Army Aviation air base at Stefanovikio.
The U.S. Army retired the OH-58 Kiowa helicopter.
The retirement of the OH-58 Kiowa helicopter left a capability gap in the U.S. Army.
The U.S. Army selected the Bell 360 Invictus as part of the Future Attack Reconnaissance Aircraft program in March 2020.
The U.S. Army selected the Sikorsky Raider X as part of the Future Attack Reconnaissance Aircraft program in March 2020.
The Future Attack Reconnaissance Aircraft program aims to fill the capability gap left by the retirement of the OH-58 Kiowa.

text:
In 2016, Croatia and Tunisia became the first nations to request the helicopters, ordering 16 and 24, respectively. Croatia received the first batch of 5 OH-58Ds at the Zadar-Zemunik air base on 30 June 2016. In early 2018, Greece was granted 70 OH-58Ds via an FMS arrangement, the type has been initially stationed at Hellenic Army Aviation air base at Stefanovikio.
In March 2020, the U.S. Army selected the Bell 360 Invictus and Sikorsky Raider X as part of the Future Attack Reconnaissance Aircraft (FARA) program to fill the capability gap left by the retirement of the OH-58.
